{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502841"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:50:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:50:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1901"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1901"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.15,0.37,0.07,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1901"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92031"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1901"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1901"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75470"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"813"},{"type":"tags","id":"1215"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1785"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31428"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92031"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with progressive deformity of his left hand, which has slowly become more noticeable over the last few years. The condition now interferes with his hobby of making furniture. He has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus. His medications include metformin and amlodipine. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and drinks one glass of wine daily. He is concerned that his lifestyle habits have caused the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His left hand shows palmar thickening with flexion contracture of the ring and little fingers (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chronic alcoholism","Working with vibrating tools","Idiopathic","Smoking","Diabetes mellitus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of Dupuytren\u0027s contracture, a progressive fibroproliferative disorder causing permanent flexion contracture of the digits. While multiple associations have been proposed, most cases are \u003Cstrong\u003Eidiopathic\u003C/strong\u003E with no clear causative factor identified.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic alcoholism\u003C/strong\u003E has been suggested as a risk factor for Dupuytren\u0027s contracture, but the evidence is inconsistent and a direct causal relationship has not been established. If he is being truthful, one glass of wine does not add up to chronic alcoholism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile manual labour and \u003Cstrong\u003Eworking with vibrating tools\u003C/strong\u003E were historically thought to contribute to the condition, more recent studies have not shown a convincing association.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmoking\u003C/strong\u003E has been associated with Dupuytren\u0027s contracture in some studies, but a direct causal relationship has not been demonstrated. The association may be related to microvascular changes or other factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with Dupuytren\u0027s contracture, and affected patients often present with more nodules but less severe contractures. However, it is unclear whether diabetes is causative or merely a comorbid condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe condition is most strongly associated with genetic and demographic factors including Northern European ancestry, male sex, older age, and positive family history. These associations support the understanding that most cases are primarily genetic or idiopathic in nature rather than caused by environmental or lifestyle factors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dupuytren\u0027s contracture is most commonly idiopathic despite various reported associations.","Risk factors include male sex, older age, Northern European ancestry, and family history.","While diabetes, smoking, and alcohol use are associated with Dupuytren\u0027s, causation has not been established."],"references":["Bayat A, McGrouther DA. Management of Dupuytren\u0027s disease\u2013clear advice for an elusive condition. The Annals of The Royal College of Surgeons of England. 2006 Jan;88(1):3-8.","Boe C, Blazar P, Iannuzzi N. Dupuytren Contractures: An Update of Recent Literature. J Hand Surg Am. 2021;46(10):896-906. doi:10.1016/j.jhsa.2021.07.005"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75470"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1901"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15503"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15503"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e39d2926-8e92-402d-8b41-aebdf1427255.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e39d2926-8e92-402d-8b41-aebdf1427255.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75470"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-16T17:34:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-16T17:34:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1901"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevision